As JIRA becomes used for many purposes within an enterprise, one common problem is that many similar custom fields are created. This is because each JIRA project may have very specific needs about what a field is named, e.g. "Account Owner" vs "Device Owner" in two different projects. The current best approach is to use a single field named "Owner" and change the field description in each project. But sometimes the project owner *really* wants a specific custom field name and then a new field is created.

I think that https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/ENTERPRISE/Scaling+JIRA suggests that performance degrades above 600 custom fields. I've personally noted that the Lucene index size grows as the number of custom fields increased, which also impacts JIRA issue update and comment performance.

My suggestion is to allow the names of custom fields to differ in each project, probably controlled via a field configuration. This would allow reuse of custom fields and improve the long-term performance of JIRA

